english:
  title: Early Summer Reflections
  author: Park Ui-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through the willow bridge, dense green abundance parts before me,
    While on the flower slope, fading crimson petals grow sparse—
    The elm has turned, and lo, it shifts to tender green,
    As I fashion fresh robes of pristine ramie cloth.

    The mulberry thins; the silkworms, already aged, grow weak,
    The grass thickens; my horse at last begins to fatten.
    For what reason have I lingered so long as a traveler?
    Though my heart yearns for home, home remains beyond my reach.
  footnotes:
    - The poem captures the transitional beauty of early summer (首夏) while exploring the melancholy of prolonged exile or travel. Each image marks a seasonal shift—from spring's abundance to summer's fullness—mirroring the speaker's own sense of temporal displacement.
    - The mention of silkworms and ramie cloth grounds the poem in the agricultural and domestic cycles of traditional East Asian life, emphasizing what the speaker has been separated from during their travels.
